# Ignore folders
bin/
obj/
node_modules/
.vscode/
.idea/
dist/
build/

# Ignore development appsettings
**/appsettings.Development.json





# In a .NET web application, you should exclude obj and certain user-specific files in Properties, but you must generally include the Migrations folder. 
# Folder Breakdown
# obj/ (Exclude): This folder contains temporary files and artifacts generated during the build process. These are auto-generated on every developer's machine and should never be committed as they cause merge conflicts and bloat the repository.
# Properties/ (Partial Exclude):
# Keep: Essential project metadata like AssemblyInfo.cs or launchSettings.json (unless it contains sensitive secrets).
# Exclude: User-specific settings files like *.user or publishProfiles/*.pubxml.user, as these contain local machine paths or personal settings.
# Migrations/ (Include): Unlike the others, this folder contains the history of your database schema changes. You need these files to sync the database schema across different environments (Development, Staging, Production) and among team members.
